node.title: How to do ductile fracture with phase-field method in MOOSE?
node.bodyText:
Hello MOOSEer,
I'm writing to ask if there are any examples on ductile fracture with phase-field method in MOOSE or other MOOSE-based applications? Thanks.

Hello
I think @tonkmr merged some models doing this. I dont know if there's a tutorial but there are test inputs
I ll let him confirm
Guillaume
I would suggest you look at https://github.com/hugary1995/raccoon
@GiudGiud is referring to https://mooseframework.inl.gov/moose/source/materials/ComputeCrackedStress.html. There is an example there with a finite strain plastic material.
Thanks !

node.title: coupledValue vs coupledScalarValue
node.bodyText:
Hello, I’m getting the following error when I try to add a coupled variable.
/home/batodon/MOOSE/projects/ergs/src/userobjects/PorousFlowBrineSaltCO2.C: In constructor 'PorousFlowBrineSaltCO2::PorousFlowBrineSaltCO2(const InputParameters&)':
/home/batodon/MOOSE/projects/ergs/src/userobjects/PorousFlowBrineSaltCO2.C:30:16: error: 'coupledValue' was not declared in this scope; did you mean 'coupledScalar'?
   30 |     _solid_sat(coupledValue("solid_sat"))

I’ve correctly declared and retrieved the variable as follows:
  const VariableValue & _solid_sat;

params.addRequiredCoupledVar("solid_sat", "ss.");

_solid_sat(coupledValue("solid_sat"))

The error disappears when I replace coupledValue with coupledScalarValue, but I want to use the former. Could you please help? Thanks.

What UserObject type is PorousFlowBrineSaltCO2?
Many UOs cannot obtain variable values because they don't have the context of a "current" element/node/etc.
Hello @loganharbour, it is a fluid_state UO. I’m guessing it’s part of those that do not accept coupled variables. Correct?

It's a fluid propery.
It does not accept coupled variables, variables should be inputs to the routines, like density_from_p_T has pressure and temperature as inputs
coupled variables should not be attributes of this user object
oh well! Thanks.

Isn't the solid saturation calculated by your user object given the pressure, temperature and salt mass fraction? I'm not sure why you want to add it as a variable here? Is it for an initial condition?

Hello @cpgr. No worries, I was testing a few ideas I had about Xnacl being equal to the solid saturation instead of XEQ in my MassFraction. I wanted the computed solid saturation at the previous time step to equal Xnacl  in the new time step. It’s a bad idea. Dw about it.

node.title: Running peacock on docker installation
node.bodyText:
Hello everyone,
I am trying to run Peacock on a Docker container in my Windows 11 machine. However, I am encountering an error that says "Peacock command not found". After some investigation, it appears that the path to the Peacock executable is not included in my environment variables.
I have been trying to locate the file where I can edit the path to include the Peacock executable, but so far, I have not been successful. Could anyone provide guidance on how to locate the file or files where I can edit the path to include the correct one for Peacock?
Thank you in advance for your help.

The Peacock executable will be located here (if you followed the directions to clone moose to ~/projects/moose:
$HOME/projects/moose/python/peacock/peacock
In order to make the above path included in your PATH environment variable permanently, add the following to your shell startup profile:
Bash users:
echo "export PATH=\$PATH:\$HOME/projects/moose/python/peacock/" >> ~/.bash_profile
Zsh users:
echo "export PATH=\$PATH:\$HOME/projects/moose/python/peacock/" >> ~/.zshrc
To figure out what shell you use (Bash, Zsh, perhaps something else):
echo $0
If this returns something other than the two common shells I posted, you'll need to do some searching on the internet on how to modify your specific shell's startup profile.

node.title: Conditional Dirichlet BCs
node.bodyText:
Is there a way to apply "conditional" Dirichlet BCs to part of a side set?  For example, say I have a simulation where I only want to apply a Dirichlet condition over a location that changes as a function time (but will always be contained within a sideset on the mesh).
For a Neumann BC this type of thing is possible: just use a FunctionNeumannBC where you apply whatever BC you want in the current/active region and zero outside of that.  The zero here won't affect the problem.
But this isn't so simple for DirichletBCs, as outside the active region I want to impose no constraint on the problem, not a zero boundary condition.
The background here is that I have a simulation where I'm trying to effectively do rigid contact but using a stiff contact surface is proving to be numerically quite difficult...

There is ElementSubdomainModifier that modifies element subdomain during the simulation. I wonder if you could follow what's in there and do something similar to sidesets/nodesets. It's going to be a custom user object.

I guess the hacky way would be to subclass PenaltyDirichletBC to take a function for the penalty term.  But I suspect that's going to put me right back in convergence purgatory.  Still, I'm desperate so maybe I'll see what happens.
Let me know if it doesn't work. I can write a SidesetModifier.

Somewhat to my surprise this worked.  So the idea is to impose the Dirichlet BC with a penalty, but then use some sort of step function for the penalty stiffness so that it's only non-zero in the region you want to impose the BC.  This seems like a very specialized type of thing to do but if there's any interest in having it in the framework I'd be happy to share the code.
Hi Mark @reverendbedford, I meet almost the same situation here (Dirichlet BC on a time-varying boundary), can you share the conditional BC you wrote?

node.title: grad_test with Tri-mesh and RZ coords
node.bodyText:
Hello:
I have an app where velocity is "constant monomial" and pressure is "Lagrange first".  This is a hybrid rDG/CG scheme that works great most of the time.  But...
computeQpResidual() for the mass conservation equation (inherited from ADKernel) whose non-linear variable is pressure has:
res = _rho[_qp] * _velocity[_qp] * _grad_test[_i][_qp];
where velocity is an ADMaterialProperty(RealVectorValue) whose components are vel_x and vel_y for this 2D problem.  The problem is a simple rectangle with uniform inlet velocity and outlet pressure BCs. I have simplified the model down so there is no momentum advection, no gravity.  Just pressure gradient and form drag.
It works great when:

The mesh is all quads and the coordinate system is either XY or RZ.  No problem.
The mesh is all tris and the coord system is XY.

It does not work if the coord system is RZ and the mesh includes tris.  To make sure this wasn't an inlet BC problem, I put a quad mesh as an inlet section and have it transition to a tri-mesh.  The attached 2 figures show the velocity magnitude for both XY and RZ systems.  The velocity should be uniform (all ve_y) with a value of 0.1.  Note the higher velocity magnitude for the RZ case for the first tri at the centerline that is due to a vel_x component.  It appears that this is caused by the residual of this mass eq for the first tri element.  It should be zero but instead has a small value that forces the radial (vel_x) velocity to be non-zero.  The flow does go to a uniform distribution further downstream.
Finally, if I offset these blocks from the centerline in the RZ system, the unphysical vel_x component gradually disappears as the block is moved further away from the centerline.
Any ideas?  Help is greatly appreciated.
Joe Kelly

Hello
In RZ, there should be an extra term for the pressure gradient, just arising from the definition of the divergence in RZ
For the first component of momentum RZ, if R is the first components (usually like this)
res += -_pressure[_qp] / _ad_q_point_qp * _test[_i][_qp];
Do you have it here?
Guillaume

For XY with a mix of quads and tris, this should have worked, we would definitely need to investigate that.
Have you tried SVD, do you know how many singular values you have? This helps guessing where the issue happens

Hi Guillaume:  For the pressure gradient term, I am not integrating by parts, so I am using:
return _eps[_qp] * _grad_pressure_qp * _test[_i][_qp];
where the non-linear vars are vel_x and vel_y.  I looked at this first, but it works perfectly for quads in RZ.  I'll try svd and get back to you.  Just about done for my Saturday workday...
Joe

For this problem, I have eliminated the momentum flux terms (for debug purposes).  So, in effect, I have turned this into a Poisson problem.  With constant fluid properties, the mass eq. simply states that div(V) = 0.  The momentum eq, is simply grad(P) = -K|V|V.
At any rate, here is the SVD output for 1st iteration:
 SVD: condition number 6.229482285046e+03, 0 of 56 singular values are (nearly) zero
  SVD: smallest singular values: 1.673742906471e-04 7.262316760914e-04 1.217246675124e-03 1.653500109633e-03 2.200366856638e-03
  SVD: largest singular values : 1.000004573129e+00 1.000082403684e+00 1.000240952341e+00 1.041314956785e+00 1.042655178559e+00

I can provide the Jacobin as well.  But everything works perfectly in RZ as long as I don't use Tri's.
Joe

Is there a good reason to integrate by parts for the pressure gradient term?  I would prefer not to as I would also need the porosity gradient.  That would cause the porosity to be an auxvar instead of a material property.
As I do some more complex geometries, even with a quad mesh, albeit one that is can be slightly skewed, I begin to see a bit of striping in the pressure in RZ.  No striping in XY.

Ok in the mass equation you did integrate by parts right?
res = _rho[_qp] * _velocity[_qp] * _grad_test[_i][_qp];
this is how you got v out of the divergence and grad_test
It should have looked like integral[ 1/r d(r rho v)/dr * test * rdr ] = integral[ d(r rho v)/dr * test dr] -> int [ (r rho v) * grad_test] + boundary term
so is there a missing r factor?
Nevermind that factor comes later, multiplying the contribution to the residual
In INS and INSAD we dont integrate it by parts.
Do you compare well to INS and INSAD results for simple RZ channels?
I'm not sure why those terms are integrated by parts or not. For diffusion terms, it's to reduce the FE order required by one.
Here it may just be to make boundary terms more or less simple.

Made a mesh to investigate that.
Works fine with INS with second order velocities, first order pressure
[Mesh]
  [inlet]
    type = CartesianMeshGenerator
    ix = 2
    iy = 4
    dim = 2
    dx = 1
    dy = 1
    subdomain_id = 2
  []

  ## add some tris
  [poly]
    type = PolyLineMeshGenerator
    points = '0.0 1.0 0.0
              0.0 2.0 0.0
              1.0 2.0 0.0
              1.0 1.0 0.0'
    loop = true
    num_edges_between_points = 2
  []
  [triang]
    type = XYDelaunayGenerator
    boundary = 'poly'
    refine_boundary = false
    desired_area = 0.2
  []
  [bot]
    type = SideSetsFromNormalsGenerator
    input = triang
    normals = '0 -1 0
               1 0 0
               -1 0 0
               0 1 0'
    new_boundary = 'bottom_tri
                    left
                    right
                    top_tri'
    replace = true
  []

  # Stitch
  [stitch]
    type = StitchedMeshGenerator
    inputs = 'inlet bot'
    stitch_boundaries_pairs = 'top bottom_tri'
    clear_stitched_boundary_ids = true
  []
  [rename_error]
    type = RenameBoundaryGenerator
    input = 'stitch'
    old_boundary = 'top'
    new_boundary = 'right'
  []
[]

Thanks for taking the time to investigate this Guillaume.  I am pretty convinced that the usual weak form of the mass advection term, namely:
res = _rho[_qp] * _velocity[_qp] * _grad_test[_i][_qp];
isn't quite perfect for RZ geometry when the velocity vars are "constant monomials" and hence essentially cell-centered finite volume vars.
I looked at INSADMass & INSMassRZ etc.  So, if one uses the strong form, then it is necessary to add the U/r term.  I thought about giving this a try but I can't use the gradient of the velocity as that is zero for monomials.
What I would really like to be able to do is use the ADDGKernel to compute the mass advection term consistent with how it is done for momentum and energy.  But my non-linear var for the mass eq. is pressure which is "Gauss first" and hence FEM.  So, I need to use CG type kernels for that.
There is probably some way to accomplish that, using DG type advection with CG, but it will take me into parts of Moose that I don't have an understanding for.  I might need to do that though when I have a good bit more time.
Thanks again for the help,
Joe

It does appear that I have a problem with skewed mesh cells, even with X-Y coords.  It really shows up when the energy eq. is turned on.  I am guessing that it is necessary for the mass/momentum/energy advection terms to all have consistent fluxes.  That is, use a DGKernel flux across the faces for all eqs.
So, the question of whether or not I can have P as a CFEM variable with others as DG (FV) is likely the real problem.  With mesh cells that are perpendicular to X-Y, the current scheme works well and avoids the checkerboard problem w/o resorting to a something like RC.
Looks like I have some work ahead of me to make this work.
Thanks again for the help.   Joe

@lindsayad thoughts?

There is probably some way to accomplish that, using DG type advection with CG

I think I agree that we d want the conservation of mass equation to look much like the conservation of momentum and energy, with the same kind of fluxes, differing only by the appropriate factor.
To do that we would need the appropriate set of test functions for that equation, maybe the same as for velocity? This seems to me like we would want to use different FE families for solution (pressure) and test functions (to write the fluxes), so a Petrov Galerkin method.

I wonder if, as an exploration, we could have the following.

add dummy nonlinear variable Z that is of the same type as velocity
use Z for the variable parameter of the mass equation, write the mass equation in a DG form
use pressure for the variable parameter of the Z equation, which is just dZ/dt = 0
This will off-course have a lot of off-diagonal terms, but a direct solver (LU with a diagonal shift for now) would handle them
